Explanation of existing data 
This section is not applicable to this experiment. 
Data collection procedures 
The sample will match the characteristics of the original study, which recruited US residents via 
Amazon Mechanical Turk (MTurk) with an approval rate of 95% of higher. The payment for the 
original study was $0.20 (Yang et al., 2013, p. 727): “One hundred nineteen participants (50.4% 
male; M age = 32.61 years, SD = 10.35 years) from Amazon.com’s Mechanical Turk (MTurk) 
participated in this experiment in exchange for $.20.” As an alteration to the original study’s 
design, we will pay participants $0.30 as per suggestion of the corresponding author. We will 
also change the type of gift card that participants are given; in the original study, Best Buy gift 
cards were used as part of the design. In this replication, we will be using Amazon vouchers 
instead.   
  
Because the corresponding author has provided their original survey/data collection 
procedures (in the form of a Qualtrics survey: https://osf.io/kwqgz/), we will use what has been 
provided and administer the replication study on our institution’s Qualtrics platform. The link to 

the replication survey can be found here: 
https://essex.eu.qualtrics.com/jfe/form/SV_9YPU5ichklHvtIN  
  
Our Qualtrics survey will replicate exactly the procedures of the original study: 1. At the 
beginning of the experiment, we will ensure participants are paying attention to the 
instructions (see our Qualtrics survey p.3-4) by using a manipulation check. The manipulation 
check provides participants with a larger body of text, instructing them at the end of the text to 
ignore the multiple-choice items on the bottom of the page and instead click on the title at the 
top of the page. This check is identical to the original study’s procedures (Yang et al., 2013, p. 
727): “To detect participants who did not pay attention to the instructions, we administered an 
instructional manipulation check (Oppenheimer, Meyvis, and Davidenko 2009) at the beginning 
of the experiment. Participants could start the experiment only after they had correctly 
answered the instructional manipulation check.” The manipulation check does not exclude 
participants; instead, it prompts participants until they provide the correct answer. 2. Next 
(Qualtrics survey p.4), participants will read task instructions and will indicate their willingness 
to pay: “We will randomly select 5 participants of this survey. If you are selected, we will give you 
$20 (in form of a bonus payment for completing this HIT), and an opportunity to purchase a 
lottery ticket. We are interested in how much you are willing to pay for the lottery ticket. The 
lottery ticket will for sure give you either a $10 Amazon gift card or a $20 Amazon gift card (both 
are equally likely). If the price you are willing to pay is equal to or above our reservation price 
for the lottery ticket, you will buy the lottery ticket at the reservation price (in this case, we will 
send you the outcome of the lottery ticket, either a $10 Amazon gift card or a $20 Amazon gift 
card). If the price you are willing to pay is below our reservation price, you will not buy the 
lottery ticket.  What's the highest price you are willing to pay for the lottery ticket?” See also 
attached excerpts from Appendix A of Yang et al. (2013), which will be included as an 
attachment in the OSF preregistration.  3. Then (Qualtrics survey p.4-5), participants will 
respond to a comprehension check item (see subsequent Analysis Plan Data Exclusion section). 
In line with the original study,  
 
  
we plan exclude participants who fail the following comprehension question: “What was the 
lowest possible outcome of the offer?” (possible response options: $0, $5, $10, $15, $20). 
Participants who fail to select the correct response ($10) will be excluded from all analyses. 4. 
Finally, participants will be told that we will contact them if they have been randomly selected to 
receive $20 bonus payment (i.e. being one of 5 people selected) and whether they will have to 
pay for the gift card or lottery ticket (i.e., if their willingness to pay is higher than our reservation 
price) (Qualtrics survey p.6). Participants then answer a few more questions: “How difficult did 
you find the instructions?” (7-point scale: 1 = not at all difficult, 7 = very difficult) (Qualtrics 
survey p.6), gender, age, and annual household income (Qualtrics survey p.6), and any 

suggestions or feedback for the study (Qualtrics survey p.6-7). At the end of the experiment, 
participants will be given a completion code so that they can receive their payment of $0.30 on 
Amazon Mechanical Turk’s platform (Qualtrics survey p.7).  
 
Qualtrics_Survey.pdfYang_JournMarketRes_2013_AppendixA.jpg 
Sample size 
The initial target analytic sample size is 162 participants. If a statistically significant effect is not 
observed after the first round of data collection, a second round will begin. The second round 
of data collection will sample an additional 200 participants for a target pooled analytic sample 
of 362 participants. 
Sample size rationale 
Power calculations were done in accordance with the guidelines of the Social Sciences 
Replication Project (SSRP). The first round of data collection achieves 90% power to detect 75% 
of the original effect size. The pooled sample, if necessary after testing the effect on the first 
round of data collection, achieves 90% power to detect 50% of the original effect size.   For this 
replication the power analysis was performed by the Center for Open Science SCORE team 
using the pwr package in R, using a script for a between subjects t-test.  
Stopping rule 
The target analytic sample size is 162 participants. After achieving that sample, planned 
analyses will be run. If a significant effect in the hypothesized direction is found, sampling stops. 
If that significant effect is not found, a second round of data collection will aim for 200 
additional usable observations, for a pooled analytic sample of 362. Sampling will stop after the 
second round of data collection regardless of a significant effect. 
  
In order to achieve the necessary sample size we will collect 208 observations in the first round 
of data collection. This sample size includes the estimated 22% of data that will be excluded due 
to the comprehension check, in line with the original study. The first round of data collection 
will stop at 208, after which the data will be analyzed. The second round of analysis will only 
occur if no initial significant effect is found. The second round of data collection also has a set 
stopping rule; no more than 257 additional observations will be collected. This would total 465 
observations, of which we expect 22% to be excluded post-data collection. 
Variables 
Manipulated variables 
A risky prospect will be framed as either a “lottery ticket” or a “gift certificate”. The instructions 
provided to participants will require participants to indicate their willingness to pay for a 
prospect (either “lottery ticket” or “gift certificate”). Excerpts from Yang et al. (2013) Appendix A 
related to this manipulated variable are attached to the OSF preregistration. 
Yang_JournMarketRes_2013_AppendixA.jpg 

Measured variables 
The main and only variable in this replication is “willingness to pay”. Participants will be asked to 
respond to the following question: “What is the highest price you are willing to pay for the [gift 
card/lottery ticket]?” Responses to this question is the “willingness to pay” variable. This variable 
is characterized as an amount in US dollar and is measured on a ratio scale. This variable will be 
measured using the same Qualtrics survey used in the original study, which has been provided 
by the corresponding author 
(https://osf.io/kwqgz/?view_only=1a2cfb0d105440c589e2e0a05cba31f0). Excerpts from Yang et 
al. (2013) Appendix A related to this measured variable are attached to the OSF preregistration. 

 
Indices 
This section is not applicable to this experiment. 
No files selected 
Analysis Plan 
Statistical models 
For the purposes of SCORE, to test H* in line with the original paper, we will use an 
independent-samples t-test. Original test and results (Yang et al., 2013, p. 727): “Participants in 

the lottery condition were willing to pay less (M = $5.68, SD = $6.69, Mdn = $5.00) than 
participants in the gift card condition (M = $9.52, SD = $4.48, Mdn = $ 7.50; t(99) = 3.43, p < .001,  
p 2 = .11; z = 2.93, p = .003; see Figure 1).” 
No files selected 
Transformations 
Per author correspondence, the willingness to pay measure was not transformed prior to 
analysis. In line with the original study, this replication will similarly not transform the measured 
variable “willingness to pay” prior to analysis 
Inference criteria 
Criteria for a successful replication attempt for the SCORE project is a statistically significant 
effect (alpha .05, a two tailed test) in the same pattern as the original study. For this replication 
attempt, this criterion is met by a significant difference in the t-test with participants in the 
lottery condition having a lower mean willingness to pay than participants in the gift card 
condition. 
Data exclusion 
Outliers or missing data will not be reason for exclusion because per author correspondence, 
data were not excluded for these reasons in the original study. However, following the original 
study, we will exclude participants who fail the following comprehension question: “What was 
the lowest possible outcome of the offer?” (possible response options: $0, $5, $10, $15, $20). 
Participants who fail to select the correct response ($10) will be excluded from all analyses. We 
expect about 25% of participant data will be excluded due to incorrectly answering the 
comprehension check, as this was the case in the original study.For more information, see Yang 
et al. (2013, p. 727): “Finally, to check whether participants erroneously believed that $0 was a 
possible payoff, participants were asked, “What was the lowest possible outcome of the offer?” 
and chose an answer from the values $0, $5, $10, $15, and $20 (Simonsohn 2009)... Fortyseven 
participants (75.8%) in the gift card condition and 54 participants (94.7%) in the lottery condition 
correctly indicated that the $10 gift card was the lowest possible outcome... In the subsequent 
analysis, we only considered responses of those who answered this question correctly.” 
Missing data 
We will not be excluding any missing data. Per author correspondence, data were not excluded 
because of missingness in the original study. 
Exploratory analysis 
This section is not applicable to this experiment. 
Other 
Other 
We will attempt to replicate the claim in the original study as faithfully as possible by using the 
original survey that was administered using the Qualtrics platform (and provided and shared by 
the original authors: https://osf.io/kwqgz/). However, since the original study was run in 2013, 

we do not know how the participant pool (Amazon Mechanical Turk workers in the US with 95% 
approval rate or higher) has changed since. For example, recent research suggests the quality 
of data from this participant pool might have fallen (Chmielewski & Kucker, 2019). 
 

